[One still wonders if HIV co-infection is playing a role in this present
outbreak. Leishmaniasis is one of the infections that are seen in
HIV-infected/AIDS patients and it is well known that the risk of developing
clinical leishmaniasis increases with decreasing CD4 count. The outbreak in
Wajir and indeed in other parts of tropical Africa can very likely be the
result of HIV-infection in the local population. Other infections or
symptoms in HIV-infected can be quite similar - fever, lymphadenopathy,
anemia, progressive emaciation, and weakness, with the hepatosplenomegaly
being attributed to other co-existing etiologies. It is important that the
authorities dealing with the outbreak report on the HIV-status of the
patients as it is possible that the outbreak reflect a stable situation
regarding _Leishmania_ but an increase in HIV-related impaired immunity.
-Mod.MPP/EP
